https://unix.stackexchange.com/questions/6979/count-total-number-of-occurrences-using-grep?newreg=a2f297ea438e4d578a581647fc51cf88

grep's -o will only output the matches, ignoring lines; wc can count them:

grep -o 'needle' file | wc -l
This will also match 'needles' or 'multineedle'.
Only single words:

grep -o '\bneedle\B' file | wc -l
# or:
grep -o '\<needle\>' file | wc -l
